Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the euro area is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 euro-zone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November - an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent was recorded after 2.6 per cent in October, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
According to Bloomberg, official forecasts are only 3 percent.
Unlike the American, British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the leitzsins. In its discretion, the reduction in interest rates would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment to the emergence of an inflation spiral.
The ECB strives to keep inflation below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a dilemma: inflation must be "agreed" in order to exclude the need for action later on.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in Germany reached a twelve-year record high in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The rise in euro-zone inflation was driven by the rise in food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations rose by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in prices for edible oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent in 2008, but is expected to decline to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup is facing a government crisis
After a long period of stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown considerably until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has had the largest base camp, while the support for the socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
Among party-faithful voters, the difference is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: more than two thirds (71 percent) are opposed to one fifth (20 percent) of support for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary threshold: they come to two percent in the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low point, the general economic mood has worsened further - never before has the proportion of those who consider the country's economic situation to be "speakably bad" been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it "quite bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, the families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate further; only one tenth is expected to improve.
A Gallup survey conducted in December showed that 71% of respondents - a historic high - rated the Prime Minister's work as "rather bad than right".
Thirteen percent of respondents have great trust or trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the share of supporters for Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% distrust of the party leader of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of those who think that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister could be managed without a change of government.
After the riots last October, 35% of the votes were in favour of the government and the head of government, but today this figure is only 20%, while the relative majority (33 percent) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked for their interest in the referendum, 60 percent replied that they would participate "with security" and another 20% would vote "probably".
By way of comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place this Sunday, only 55 percent would go to the polls "with certainty" and another 15 percent would consider their participation "probably". In view of these tendencies, the result of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against hospital daily allowance.
Put on the group of those who took part in the referendum "with security" the proportions of opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would be even 81, 84, and 89 percent respectively.
