Obviously, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers - after all, they were able to pass the drastic price increase on to the multinationals.
In the golden trade triangle, hypermarkets do not complain; good years are constantly reported.
Our experience shows that the majority of customers in the three department stores no longer look at prices.
It is bought from all large quantities, durable foods go in pallets over the counters.
Wednesday morning in the morning there were endless queues at the cash desk in all three department stores, when suddenly the number of customers exploded.
However, a lower customer frequency is reported by the country, so many multinationals complain to opinion researchers that they cannot even achieve the planned turnover, not only for food, but also for sustainable consumer goods.
In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
Hygiene conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overloading of staff - all factors that are not conducive to the containment of infections, according to the leading doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
The traumatology department of János Hospital recently diagnosed MRSA infection.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient has been isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured person in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with a MRSA infection. Since then, an important operation could not be performed due to the bacterium, which is still in the patient’s body.
Until 10 December this year, infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System from hospitals in 1094, according to Karolina Böröcz, head of the National Epidemiology Centre.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were registered in hospitals with certainty, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their noses without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the drugs are dosed too high or used improperly, the well-responding bacteria result in antibiotic-resistant bacteria that spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with a weakened or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday sick home life.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA there is only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nurses wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment," says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are being examined for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for curbing the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and old people's homes, hospitals should examine the patients in the hospital and immediately isolate MRSA infected patients.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not so common.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state health insurance fund for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology centre.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always adhered to by hospitals.
According to Karolina Böröcz, microbiological sampling is even more rare among outpatients or patients in primary care.
Saved by disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transferred from one patient to the other by nursing staff.
It is precisely for this reason that hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient in the local hospitals.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds narrowly lined up, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz points out, unfortunately, in the less financially well-placed hospitals it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that actually favour the emergence of infections.
Such infections have been shown to be far less common there, or can be prevented from spreading the pathogen where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes enormous costs to health insurance companies, so they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government programme.
After initial signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has identified the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
Death Lover Policeman Was Not Drunk
In the case of the car accident with fatal outcome caused by the police chief of the XXII district, the official report is now available.
The now resigned police chief of the XXII district, who killed a pedestrian in a car accident on Tuesday, was neither alcoholized nor under the influence of drugs, said Attila Morvai, the press spokesman of the Budapest Supreme Prosecutor's Office on Friday, after the official report on the case was submitted.
The report confirmed the results of the initial investigation, according to which the police chief had not consumed alcohol before he took the wheel.
The former police chief took his own car to Kossuth Lajos Street in the XXII district and ran over a 55-year-old man who crossed the street at an unmarked location.
(According to StVO, however, this is not a mitigating circumstance - the handlebars have, even if pedestrians do not cross the road on the zebra strip, rank.)
