A further EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Minister of Finance János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements in Budapest on Friday with a total value of EUR 400 million to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental projects implemented with grants from the Cohesion Fund.The loan agreement for EUR 100 million has already been signed earlier and the current agreement deals with the use of the EUR 200 million granted.
The sum of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement will also be spent on the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has allocated a total of EUR 300 million to Hungary for this purpose and the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later in the context of the extension of the loan agreement.
In the area of innovation, the contracting parties have signed an agreement of EUR 50 million, which will mainly be channelled into research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
At the meeting, the subway line 4 was also mentioned.
It was agreed that once Hungary has clarified the details of the underground financing with the EU, the original contract and possible modifications will be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects totalling EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan interest is EURIBOR-linked, the loan is provided by the EIB with a deferral of 8 years, without commission.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe looks attentively at the former rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who still buys the cheapest market in the EU, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most sought-after roadblock for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains, the Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa regions are among the most popular, along the sea are Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are increasingly in demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will also attract investors sooner or later, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the extremely favorable area of Russe has more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - trade and office space offer highest returns.
Bulgaria is on the best way to become one of the most attractive European golfers' paradises, and thus to attract tourists in addition to the summer and winter season as well in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying in on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who purchase real estate in Bulgaria are also seeking to change their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down will either buy revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or run-down houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they will then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are important, but the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are also crucial for buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of businessmen who invest in order to increase medium to long-term value.
However, real estate in the capital is constantly becoming more expensive due to the ever-growing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are lowest in Bulgaria, but there has been an annual increase of 21 percent over the past five years.
The price increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission-reducing measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the Kyoto Protocol expires.
There is currently a fierce debate between developed and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but they would be prepared to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major question of the conference is whether the developed countries are prepared to support developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on support for developing countries has also been reached.
The adjustment fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, probably at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be seen in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's six percent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by 1990 values), regardless of whether the "Agreement after 2012" was successful or not. The Union would even be prepared to commit itself to a 30% reduction if other major industrialised countries in the world, or developing countries, are also prepared to fulfil their commitments to the fullest extent possible and responsibly.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the goal of the countries that had joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU, with its 15 member states at the time, had already committed itself to a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will certainly meet, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The deployment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction plans set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a renewed international emission reduction system, the importance of which was also underlined by the IPCC, the international scientific climate change committee of the UN, which was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in its recent report.
This would delay emissions reduction and increase the average temperature of the earth by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, which would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British army advertises on YouTube
British Army units have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First of all, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special Forces stationed in Afghanistan have been downloading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The images shot with miniature cameras mounted on helmets are controlled at the Kandahar Air Force base and then sent to London, where they are posted on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Soldiers of the Luftwaffe have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Department of Defense was registered under Defenceheadquarters in spring 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Department of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peacekeeping Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Luftwaffe published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of the foreign operations.
According to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie of the BBC, propaganda published in this way is almost free of charge, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
American advertise with game
But the army also has to fight against amateur recordings, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored recordings, also make it into the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are discussed at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, numerous videos of the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "genus" for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "Americas Army", in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less life-scattered simulation.
