More and more forces mobilized for giant strike
On Friday, the League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Trade Union Federation will form their coordinating committee for the indefinite strike starting on Monday.
On Saturday, a major protest meeting will be held, and on Monday - on the day of the referendum on the Health Insurance Act - the stoppage of work will begin.
Strike-related, significant traffic obstructions are expected, as rail transport is almost completely stopped, and Budapest's public transport companies (BKV) are also on strike until 1 p.m.
Details of the Monday strike will be announced by the League of Trade Unions and the Federation of Trade Unions on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA - MOSZ strike committee is also set up, which is responsible for coordinating the actions on Monday.
On Saturday, a large-scale protest meeting will be held, and on Monday, all organizations that have joined the strike will cease work indefinitely unless agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike, which began on the day of the parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act, was not defined.
If the National Council does not accept the Health Insurance Act, the unions immediately withdraw the call for strike.
However, if the law is adopted, the strike committees will meet to discuss further action.
On the basis of the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even conceivable that there will be a vote on the Health Insurance Act only in the late evening hours, or even at midnight.
The strikes starting on Monday will have to be expected to cause considerable traffic disruptions: the railway workers lay down their work for an indefinite period of time, in the morning the majority of public transport and more than half of the Volán companies will stop.
At the same time, there will be motorway blocks in many places in one direction.
The call for strike has been followed by numerous trade unions and civil organizations - the list of participants is constantly updated on the League website.
Some organizations announced strikes for an indefinite period of time, while others are planning a temporary stoppage of work.
Until Thursday afternoon, no agreement was reached between the Hungarian Railway MÁV and the Free Union of Railway Workers VDSZSZ on sufficient services, even though more and more people are travelling by train just around Christmas holidays.
According to previous reports, the BKV is on strike from the start of operations until 1 p.m., at Budapest Airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the LIGA power and heat energy unions are putting down work for four hours, and the teachers' union, bwz. the Democratic Teachers' Union, have called for 2- or 2-8 hour strikes.
The Hungarian Medical Association is on an alternating strike nationwide at various times, the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organisation of the SCEF, the forum for trade union cooperation, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government withdraws the draft health insurance reform and presents a new concept for social discourse.
The second requirement concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, which will be due from next year.
Claim number three states that the eligible occupational groups will be allowed access to the early retirement scheme before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, a member of the League of Trade Unions, did not accept the offer submitted by the Ministry of Transport concerning the secondary lines and is now calling for a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
Among other things, the Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states that in the context of the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "enhancement of the existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsies and non-Gypsy populations in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provoking such an argument, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of political leaders: "People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary conflict".
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent confrontations.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention of the local and foreign media, "have seriously damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember that since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been on the upswing, so that since summer 2007 several organizations called "National Self-Defense Association" have been founded.
"These groups are common to each of them to define themselves as a civil organisation, while openly boasting that they are preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defence tasks (catastrophe protection, national defence, order protection), relying on the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state itself," it said.
And further: All this should be done in accordance with the method that tries to disguise various political aspirations as bourgeois initiatives based on the political and party displeasure of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association are therefore not merely intended to circumvent legal hurdles that might arise in the course of registration at the court - it is also a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-enhancing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, as some ultra-nationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as confirming its own anti-Hungary policy.
All this has an impact on the political stability of the region" - it said.
From the point of view of the Research Institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central-Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was founded in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard stood the Roma mass riots that took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU has taken the incidents as a starting point for the establishment of the National Guard, arguing that the aim of the organization is "national protection".
