Holidays are not everywhere
In Hungary, holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of redistributing the working days around the holidays has become established, but the coming year will bring us less such days.
In the EU and in America, too, there is something else called "Feiertag".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and days off work.
Days off work are mostly church holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year's Eve: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are working days - the latter alone so that the New Year's Eve celebrations can rest.
All year round we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are March 15, which commemorates the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, the Memorial Day of the Revolution of 1956.
On 20 August the foundation of the state will be celebrated, on 1 May the work will be celebrated, on 1 and 2 November we will commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "shifting work days" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is to be finally processed, has been laid down by the Minister of Labour in a separate regulation for many years.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, public employees and civil servants alike.
Excluded are only companies and institutions in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on the holidays.
This year, only the holidays at the end of the year will confuse the working order somewhat: from 24 December, life in this country will be formally stopped, since most people take time compensation for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the holiday that has been reserved for this purpose.
Next year, there will be more holidays in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so that there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday 26 April will be a working day so that Friday 2 May can be a rest day.
The second rescheduling is related to the holiday on October 23rd: on Saturday, October 18th, Friday, October 24th will have to be worked out in advance.
The end of the year, however, will be completely marked by the holidays, after everything has fallen and stopped from December 24th, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six daunting little things to annoy workmates
E-mails that we forget to send, language messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we no longer notice: they bring "color" into everyday life at the workplace.
The question is simply whether you get used to these little inconveniences, or if you better face the challenge and try to consciously avoid them for other annoying situations.
Tips.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone from the marketing department called" - says a colleague.
That it missed a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it by perhaps calling the marketing department and confessing with regret that you forgot to align the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, it's all over with an apology.
Before getting involved in embarrassing excuses, consider what really makes your colleagues uncomfortable and try to avoid these situations consciously.
Borrowing something that doesn't belong to you?
There's hardly anything more annoying than grabbing a document, office supplies, or the phone, but it's not there.
Yesterday the notebook was still on the desk - this morning it's gone?
Or is the lost ballpoint pen discovered on a colleague's desk?
Without asking questions, we should not borrow anything from our colleagues, because they are rightly upset when they find that something has gone away.
So don't put envelopes or post-it from the office in your pocket, because it could hit you yourself: no more there if you really need it.
Talking about colleagues' private lives?
There is no effective means of stopping a gossip that has already been born.
Who did what with who?
Where and why?
If possible, you should not tie the information (or guesses) about the private life of your colleagues to everyone's nose!
And if someone opens up and reveals his innermost secret, we should not abuse that trust!
It is best to remain silent like a grave, rather than to direct the one who is not present, even if others know about the problems of the colleague.
Reported sick for no reason?
If you call in the office to report ill with reference to agonizing headaches, because you feel uncomfortable right now, or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: your own work, unstoppable executions, projects with fixed appointments now have to be done by your colleagues instead of yourself.
So don't play bad with your colleagues!
If you already know the day before that you won't be able to get into the office the next day, or that something could come in between, so you have to stay at home, you should report it in time so that neither the colleagues nor the boss are unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
Sum, giggling, phone calls
One is very much in the way of his work, but is suddenly disturbed by the loud giggling of his colleagues?
Is there an unwanted telephone conversation you shouldn't have heard?
One should not annoy colleagues with buzzing, singing, loud conversations (which one leads over their heads), taunting, constantly scolding or nagging.
All of this can be very disturbing, even if they are not exactly deepened in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Is it always the others' fault?
If a project is not completed on time, one has forgotten to send an important letter or important messages, one should not look for the guilt of one's own forgetfulness with others!
If possible, you should not talk about the chaos in the office or the noisy colleagues!
It is best to admit your mistakes and apologize if others were affected!
The question of how to make up for the mistake or how to make up for what is missing is all too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like home?
Training pants and slaps: Comfortable for home, but has nothing lost in the office!
Not even then should one dress so casually, if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself to the extent that you dress accordingly in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
