Banks want to cope with crisis
The American Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis on the financial markets.
For example, more than $100 billion will go to the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, the banks auction interest rates to which they are willing to lend each other money.
For example, the American Fed is sending $40 billion to auction, and another $24 is making it loose for the European and Swiss central banks.
After the September 11 attacks, it is the first time that national central banks have agreed on such a coordinated approach to countering or mitigating the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This step is intended to eliminate the biggest difficulties of the economy, i.e. the increasing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend," wrote Bernard Baumohl of the Economic Outlook Group consultancy in a report for his clients.
"The coordinated action of central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the US from 65% to about 50%," added Baumohl in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion because of unserved loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect further billions of dollars to be lost.
"The central banks must have been really afraid of what could still happen when they decided to do so," said the chief economist of ABN Amro, Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he continued.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have hard access to bonds, loans will also be more expensive for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into recession, possibly affecting economic growth around the world.
The central banks have decided to reduce the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank interest rate, which is used in the lending of money between banks.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid to lend each other money, even though the central banks of the US, Canada and Britain had lowered their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"This will have the same effect as a further reduction in interest rates," said Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting of Reuters.
