600,000 people failed to exchange their driver's license
600000 drivers missed the deadline to exchange their old driving licence, which expires at the end of the year.
Today is the last day where you can apply for an exchange so that the authorities can issue a new driving licence by the end of the year.
However, the ministry does not fear that after New Year hundreds of thousands of drivers will go to the streets without a valid driving licence.
According to the authorities, mainly those who do not want to drive have not changed their driving licence.
While small towns report a sharp drop in interest in the exchange of tickets, the offices of the capital are being filled with applications, and interest in the exchange grew this week.
The city administration manufactures around 2000 customers daily.
You have to wait about half an hour.
In Prague about 140000 drivers have not changed their driver's license yet.
The issue of a new driving license lasts 20 days.
But it is possible to apply for the exhibition with a shortened period of five days.
In this case, however, the driver has to pay 500 crowns.
Motorists who fail to make the required exchange by the end of the year and leave without a valid driving licence are facing a fine from January onwards.
The culprit pays a maximum of 2000 kroner.
But the police can also leave it with an admonition when committing transgression.
In the event of a violation, the penalty may rise to 2500 crowns.
According to previous information, even the one who does not drive can get a penalty imposed by the municipality.
It was said that he could face a penalty of even 30,000 kroner.
The ministry has already called on the offices to exercise mildness and impose a maximum penalty of 1000 kroner.
According to the spokesman of the Ministry of Transport, Karel Hanzelka, no one threatened a thousand crown sentence.
The driving licence was a document where everyone could decide whether or not to own it.
It is not an identity card that everyone, and indeed a valid one, must have.
People who don't want to drive anymore should give up their license.
It is sufficient to take him to the competent municipal office or to send him there by registered letter.
At the end of the year, driving licences issued between 1964 and 1993 will become invalid.
However, drivers will have to gradually exchange other types of driving licences.
People with driving licences from 1994 to 2000 still have three years to exchange.
The validity of driving licences issued between 2001 and 2004 expires in December 2013.
According to Hanzelka, this is about 2.6 million more driving licences.
