Cuba - most beautiful island of the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday will come true if you only choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palm trees and all inclusive with waiters who offer pizza, ice cream and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
But only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place ever seen by a human eye.
Havana once became a camp or transit camp of treasures that the Spaniards had robbed in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the very end of the 20th century.
One of the chiefs of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, built it because everything that was considered a crime in the US (especially during prohibition) was gladly seen and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
==References====External links==
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rises grew, and across the broad boulevards were cars that were among the cult symbols of the 1950s.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht lying.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Havana Bodeguita.
At the bar at the Hotel Nacional you can mix cocktails as you wish.
And the cult cars of the 1950s drive around in Havana to this day, because the once imported Schigulis and Fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and damp air.
If Havana, in particular its oldest part, is severely run down, nowhere can you find as many wonderful colonial sights as here.
Other places are being cleaned up, such as Trinidad.
With regard to the fact that tourism brings much needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have been created not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a moat that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam- and diesel-powered narrow-gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see clean and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have long been in the museum elsewhere.
Excursion destinations
Most of Cuba's visitors do not miss the most important places.
So you don't have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail anymore.
The only thing to mention is that there is a museum in the aforementioned Hemingways estate, the visit of which should not be missed by anyone who likes this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on calcareous soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities fertile soil was accumulated, through which also weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet him when you visit one of Havana's cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was shot there.
Trinidad
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
The trade in slaves and sugar brought fame and wealth to her.
The wealth was embodied in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that in the 1950s there was no road connecting the area to the rest of the country.
This isolation helped to keep it unattended.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was torn down, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than an afternoon for Trinidad, it is worth seeing interesting places in the area, such as the Playa Ancón beach or the "Valley of Sugar Mills".
In the evening you should go to the Casa de la Música, which revives after the darkness, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This town in the east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful of the island.
Surely this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads, which lead from Guantánamo to it, have to overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is hardly touched by human intervention.
Thanks to its untouched nature, UNESCO included this eastern outpost in its World Heritage List.
The best chocolate is produced there, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the journeys of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, you can see several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, about all this one could write many pages.
But, as they say, look better with your own eyes.
