For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was brought before a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been charged with insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced on Thursday evening by a court in Khartoum to 15 days in prison and subsequent expulsion.
The British woman was accused of having allowed six to seven-year-old students to give a teddy bear the name Mahomet, although any representation of the Islamic Prophet is forbidden.
She deserves to be flogged.
After parents of students complained several times to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture, the 54-year-old primary school teacher, who worked at the Unity High School in Khartoum, was picked up at home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September, when the teacher asks her six to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children propose eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed , reports headmaster Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Certainly, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all also a very common first name in Sudan.
Afterwards the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed .
The bear himself did not wear a shield with that name, but the problem is quite simple that the portrayal of the Islamic prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
One of the Muslim colleagues of Gillian Gibbons, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said that he knows them well, and that she never did anything that would have allowed her to get too close to a religious faith, I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his view it is only an innocent mistake.
An opinion shared by numerous students of the teacher who describe it as very attentive to their students and as a person who never speaks about religion in the class.
Consider that the first name Mohammed is also the second most frequently given second name in Britain, for which 14 different spellings exist in English.
This name, often chosen by Muslim families, is regarded as a kind of homage to the Prophet (it is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
For example, can you give it to a toy?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
On Wednesday, at the last meeting of the negotiations in Vienna, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province.
At the end of the failure
The Serbs and Albanians from Kosovo ended a sixth and final discussion session in Baden, Austria, Wednesday morning, without being able to overcome their controversies about the future status of the separatist province.
It is regrettable that the parties were unable to reach agreement on the status , said European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace in the region is at stake, its American counterpart, Frank Wilsner, called on Belgrade and Pristina to fulfil their commitments to maintain peace and to continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
No violence is expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time, he added, indicating that there are quite clear tensions.
End of placements on 10 December
The mediators of the Troika, which unites the European Union, the US and Russia, will meet for the last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of 90% of the Albanian-speaking inhabited province could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submitted their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks of Baden, near Vienna, formed the sixth and final negotiating meeting since the Troika had received a mandate from the UN last August for a new mediation.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation to end on 10 December.
The Russians, who had already blocked the granting of Kosovo's independence to the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this final date.
Russia was and remains the advocate of a negotiated solution, a mutually agreed solution, said Botsane-Khartchenko.
One-sided declaration of independence?
After eight years of Kosovo being under the administration of the UN, the Western countries consider independence under EU supervision to be the only solution with a future.
Pristina is willing to proclaim this unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in their favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy
Unfortunately, no agreement could be reached, announced Fatmir Sejdiu, president of Kosovo's autonomous authority, at the hotel in Baden, where these negotiations have been conducted since Monday of the last opportunity.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovar rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regret.
He added, however, that the plan proposed by Belgrade included the autonomy of a past that led to murders and deportations.
Domino Effect
Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, believed that a compromise should always be sought and warned the Albanian majority from Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence of the province.
Belgrade believes that it particularly favors a "domino effect" in a region that is still so much weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
For Serbia, this does not mean that a compromise would be impossible, he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision be taken solely in the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto right.
The Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word
Only a decision from the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia, said Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica.
These negotiations took two years.
They must end up as they have begun: in the Security Council.
The journalists were told by Fatmir Sejdiu that Kosovo's parliament would have the last word on status, and added that any unilateral declaration of independence from the Albanian-speaking population would take place in consultation with the Western countries.
