A Heavy Memory
After being kept confidential for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are located in Bad Arolsen over a total length of 27 km, could not be viewed until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, that is, individual and name-related, i.e. by questioning a former victim or his relatives.
The eleven states responsible for their administration, including Germany, France, Israel and the USA, agreed in May 2006 to make it accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Cheerful information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to conduct investigations, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of the forced labourers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like, for example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The prison records of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo were collected after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen still handle tens of thousands of personal inquiries.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
One should not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, declared Pr. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Antisemitism of the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
