The Congress agreed to the MIFID Directive, which entered into force on 1 November.
In parallel with the parliamentary drafting, which ended its session today with the Congress decision in the Senate on the additional/amendments related to the project, the government published the provisions resulting from the new law with the intention of enabling the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of Congress and Senate members, who in their negotiations and votes had the aim of establishing the best possible regulation, which ensures the security of investors and regulates the individual entrepreneurial activities, in order to guarantee a generally efficient market activity.
In addition to modernising financial markets, the MIFID, which re-establishes the Investment Services Regulation, is pursuing an improvement in investor protection, an increase in the rights of control of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and the promotion of cooperation between the various control authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive allows financial advisory services to be offered to specialised firms as well as to natural or legal persons, and also contributes to the creation of new financial services companies (ESIS), the consultancy companies that join forces with investment and brokerage companies in securities.
It also extends the number of systems for carrying out financial transactions so that the regulated circulation markets are added to the multilateral systems of securities trading and the systems for internationalising trading orders, which would eventually compete with current economic operators.
