Venus was perhaps once a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from an orbital European spaceship show that the planet resembles an averted twin of the Earth even more than was previously aware.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, on Venus, conditions that would have been very similar to those on Earth and could have even been habitable, scientists believe today.
But because of the unbridled carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation and a slower rotational pace, Venus took a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the space probe Venus Express of the European Space Agency, which has examined the planet for one year, offer a sobering look at how the Earth could develop in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Physics Department at Oxford University, one of the heads of the Venus Express mission, said, "It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar."
