Pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has discovered another pit to fall in; his way out of this remains the same.
For British scandals this is not particularly slippery.
No titles seem to have been sold, no politicians paid Paris hotel bills, no extramarital toes sucked.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman has concealed donations to the British ruling Labour Party for more than £650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years under the name of other people, and that the party has failed to report this, is something that the contested Gordon Brown would have done well without.
Two months ago, when the Prime Minister had withdrawn from the call for an election, stupidly insulting the intelligence of the British by claiming that opinion polls did not influence this decision, there was hope that he would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly perceptive leader of the Liberal Democrats, put it, Stalin's once feared Brown has evolved into Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of Northern Rock, a battered bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to amend tax laws have brought business associations against the government.
The tax-administrative loss of personal data of 25 million people revealed unimaginable administrative fraud.
A trio of retired generals started an uprising in the upper house in protest against cuts in military spending: to be a minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there is the manifold donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour's Secretary General (and its former Head of Fulfillment) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown is irrevocably leaving.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a turning point that makes it impossible for them to rule.
People neither like nor trust politicians, but they usually hold back their scepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it is clear that it is unlikely that a prime minister will improve the situation, and he does not even need to be there for long, this delay is over: the public service is beginning to leak; the cabinet ministers are beginning to chat; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown's position is particularly difficult because unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he would like to deny Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant-in-chief.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction documents, for example, are related to decisions made by Brown as Chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in Blair's mishap - as with the long "money for noble titles" investigation of political party financing - voters may assume it was him.
Still, Brown's situation isn't as bad as it looks
The faults are not as terrible as the Conservatives describe them.
Like Mr. Bean, no one died, or was completely deceived.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown's naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The new drive for political donations is a good example.
The garboesque Abrahams, who compares his donations with his charitable gifts, says he does not want public recognition for his goodwill.
That may be true, but he was not entitled to make the decision.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear and exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham's agreement, but not that it is illegal, will of course have to ask himself some questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour's main financial collector, who was told about the weird donations in October.
But so far Brown has not been involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he watered down this determination by grasping for a well-known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - to make the measure full, by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, "the lessons to be learned" are not very complicated.
If the law is broken, it's a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things that Mr Brown has to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the independent committee on public standards, which has been vacant for six months, and moving forward with a radical reform of political party financing.
This would require the hardliners of the Labour to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly to give up the special financial relationship with the trade unions - bitter pills for a party comrade like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some partial facts.
Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; they have two years to win back voters; and the only way to achieve victory is through unchallenged integrity and solid competence.
