Is the credit crisis affecting America's credit card market?
If there's blood in the water, it's only natural that back fins swirl around excitedly.
Now that America's real estate market is ailing, predators are targeting the country's credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts expect credit card losses to reach $99 billion if the risk of underfunded loans spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both debits and default rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are not recoverable or more than 30 days late.
Last month, HSBC announced that it has taken a $1.4 billion fee collection from its American consumer finance, partly due to the weakness of credit card holders.
It's still too early to panic.
Losses and defaults are still low.
According to Moody, the 3rd quarter default rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
An amendment to the US private insolvency laws in 2005 led to an abrupt case of bankruptcy filings, which in turn account for a large part of the credit card loss; the number of filings (and thus default fees) would rise again, whether the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate or not.
Industry also reports sound payment rates showing how much of its debt consumers pay off every month
and confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stalemate in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research company, expects that the output volumes for 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct infection channels between the real estate credit crisis and the credit card market: it is more likely that consumers take credit card debt, now that home loans dry out.
However, card issuers look at the flow of money instead of capital, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower's creditworthiness.
They can even be of benefit to card issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue to pay mortgage rates fall if the real estate is less valuable than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among redemption priorities.
Card issuers can also react much faster and more flexibly than lenders to the stormier conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of the assets.
"We won't wake up one day and reassess the loans completely," says Gary Perlin, Capital One's Chief Financial Officer.
Even if a sudden undercover crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are much more real.
If lower house prices and a credit reduction push America into recession, industry will undoubtedly face a more grim future.
