Venus is the infernal twin of the earth
Despite its hostile atmosphere on Earth, Venus is more similar than previously thought: the European "Venus Express" spacecraft has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices on the poles, as they also occur on Earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists have suspected that it is flashing on Venus.
Now the European "Venus Express" probe has provided evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere: The lightnings on Venus shoot from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 56 kilometres, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "prime soup theory", lightning has created life on earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there was ever life there, it must have been in very early history," says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on earth, sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the devil's twin on earth, but it is a twin," Russel said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has taken such a completely different development, is the fundamental question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the early 1990s no probe has been on its way specifically to explore this planet.
According to the researchers, the latest research results, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underline the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighboring planet with Earth are greater than initially assumed," the Esa informs.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents on the earthly winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers headed by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second-tinted planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is almost as large with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, revolves around the sun in just under 225 days.
But it turns much slower around itself: A Venus day lasts 243 earth days.
Although Venus hardly reminds the Earth with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that both planets were created under very similar conditions.
On both of them water was collected, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on which Venus was lost into space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed in carbonate rocks on Earth, it accounts for the majority of the atmosphere on Venus.
